{
  "id": "019d240d-e7a8-7ac2-b76e-344384c64539",
  "content": "# Hook System Rust Migration — Design Exploration (2026-03-25)\n\n## The Ownership Problem\n\nMoving hooks to Rust blurs the line between product and workspace. Three possible architectures:\n\n### Option A: `corvia hooks run` CLI subcommand (Product-owned runner)\n\n```\n.claude/settings.json → \"corvia hooks run --event PreToolUse\"\n                          ↓ (single binary, reads stdin JSON)\n                          corvia-cli dispatches to Rust handler\n                          ↓\n                          corvia-telemetry spans emitted\n                          ↓\n                          stdout JSON response to Claude Code\n```\n\n**Pros**: Full telemetry, typed events, single process, testable with cargo test\n**Cons**: Product binary handles workspace-specific logic (doc paths, session recording). Creates tight coupling between Claude Code hook protocol and corvia CLI. Every workspace using corvia would get the same hook behavior.\n\n### Option B: Separate `corvia-hooks` binary (Workspace-owned runner)\n\n```\n.claude/settings.json → \"corvia-hooks --event PreToolUse\"\n                          ↓ (standalone binary in workspace)\n                          Reads corvia.toml for config\n                          ↓\n                          Links corvia-telemetry for spans\n                          ↓\n                          stdout JSON response\n```\n\n**Pros**: Clean separation — workspace owns the binary and its behavior. Can be customized per workspace. Product provides the library, workspace builds the runner.\n**Cons**: Another binary to build/distribute. Workspace-level Rust code needs its own crate.\n\n### Option C: `corvia hooks run` with pluggable hook registry (Hybrid)\n\n```\ncorvia.toml:\n[hooks]\nsession_recording = true          # product-provided hook\ndoc_placement = true              # product-provided hook  \nagent_check = true                # product-provided hook\ncustom = [\n  { event = \"PostToolUse\", command = \"bash custom.sh\" }\n]\n\n.claude/settings.json → \"corvia hooks run --event PreToolUse\"\n                          ↓\n                          corvia-cli reads [hooks] config\n                          ↓\n                          Runs built-in handlers (Rust, with telemetry)\n                          ↓\n                          Runs custom handlers (subprocess, legacy bash)\n                          ↓\n                          Merges results, returns to Claude Code\n```\n\n**Pros**: Product provides sensible defaults with telemetry. Workspace can extend with custom hooks. Config-driven — enable/disable per workspace. Clear what's product vs custom.\n**Cons**: Most complex. Hook ordering and result merging needs careful design.\n\n## Telemetry Integration Design\n\nNew span constants needed:\n- `corvia.hook.dispatch` — top-level span for hook event processing\n- `corvia.hook.session_record` — session JSONL write\n- `corvia.hook.doc_placement` — doc validation\n- `corvia.hook.agent_check` — agent registration\n- `corvia.hook.custom` — user-defined hook execution\n\nEach hook execution emits:\n- Duration (ms)\n- Exit status (success/block/error)\n- Hook name\n- Event type (PreToolUse, PostToolUse, etc.)\n- Error message (if any)\n\n## Session Recording in Rust\n\nReplace 5 bash scripts with typed event structs:\n```rust\nenum HookEvent {\n    SessionStart { session_id, workspace, git_branch, agent_type },\n    UserPrompt { session_id, turn, content },\n    ToolStart { session_id, turn, tool, input },\n    ToolEnd { session_id, turn, tool, output, success },\n    SessionEnd { session_id, total_turns, duration_ms },\n}\n```\n\nBenefits:\n- Schema validation at compile time\n- Atomic file writes with proper locking\n- Turn counter managed in-memory (single process across events)\n- Telemetry spans around each event\n- No jq dependency, no shell expansion risks\n\n## Key Decision Needed\n\nThe fundamental question: **Is session recording a product feature or a workspace integration?**\n\n- If product feature → Option A or C, lives in corvia-cli\n- If workspace integration → Option B, lives in workspace tooling\n- If both → Option C with session recording as a built-in product hook that workspaces enable via config",
